VALUES
(1, 1, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'let them be for lights in the firmament of the heaven', 4, 57, 'connection', 'Creation of Lights', 'This phrase connects to Genesis 1:14, where God first speaks of the lights created to separate day from night. This shows the intentionality behind creation, establishing order and purpose in the cosmos. Furthermore, Psalm 19:1–4 reflects on how the heavens declare God''s glory, emphasizing the significance of these lights as a means of revelation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:14", "description": "God''s command regarding lights for day and night"}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 19:1-4", "description": "Heavens declaring the glory of God"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'to give light upon the earth', 58, 86, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Light', 'The phrase ''to give light upon the earth'' symbolizes God''s provision and guidance. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological theme of light representing purity, truth, and divine presence throughout Scripture. In John 8:12, Jesus refers to Himself as the ''light of the world,'' indicating that this creation of light foreshadows the ultimate revelation of God in Christ.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 8:12", "description": "Jesus as the light of the world"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'and it was so.', 88, 102, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Authority', 'What does the phrase ''and it was so'' reveal about the nature of God''s authority and the power of His word in creation? How does this shape our understanding of God''s promises in our lives today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the greater light to rule the day', 31, 64, 'connection', 'Daylight and Creation', 'The phrase ''the greater light to rule the day'' can be cross-referenced with Psalm 104:19, which states, ''He made the moon for the seasons; the sun knows its setting.'' This connection emphasizes God''s sovereignty over time and seasons, illustrating how the sun serves not only as a source of physical light but also as a marker for divine order in creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 104:19", "description": "Shows God''s control over celestial bodies and time"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'the lesser light to rule the night', 70, 104, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Light', 'This passage suggests a theological framework where light symbolizes knowledge, goodness, and divine presence, while darkness represents ignorance and evil. Many scholars believe that by creating a lesser light for the night, God is highlighting the continual presence of His order and guidance, even in times of darkness.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'he made the stars also', 106, 128, 'greek', 'Creation of Stars', 'כּוֹכָב (kokhav, H3556) - star, heavenly body. This Hebrew term emphasizes not only the physical creation of stars but also their role as symbols of hope and guidance in the biblical narrative, reflecting God''s glory in the heavens.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3556", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for star"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'And God made two great lights', 0, 29, 'question', 'Purpose of Creation', 'What does it mean for God to make ''two great lights,'' and how does this duality reflect His character in our lives? Consider how these lights not only serve practical purposes but also symbolize the balance of power and presence in the world.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'And God set them in the firmament of the heaven to give light upon the earth,', 0, 77, 'connection', 'Creation of Lights', 'This verse connects to Psalm 19:1, which states, ''The heavens declare the glory of God; the skies proclaim the work of his hands.'' Both passages emphasize the role of celestial bodies in revealing God''s glory and order in creation. Understanding this connection enhances our appreciation of how the created order serves not only practical purposes but also theological ones.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 19:1", "description": "Highlights the function of creation in proclaiming God''s glory."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'set them in the firmament', 8, 33, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Creation', 'This phrase suggests God''s sovereign authority in creation. Many scholars believe that the act of ''setting'' implies a purposeful design, reflecting God''s intentionality in establishing the order of the universe. This perspective encourages believers to view the cosmos not as random but as a deliberate expression of God''s will.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 1:14-19", "description": "Discusses God''s intentional design in the creation narrative."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'give light upon the earth', 51, 76, 'question', 'Purpose of Light', 'What does it mean for God to ''give light upon the earth''? Consider how this divine provision of light symbolizes guidance and truth in our lives. How does recognizing God as the source of light influence your daily decisions and moral compass?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'to rule over the day and over the night', 4, 43, 'connection', 'Ruling Authority in Creation', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 104:19, which states, ''He made the moon for the seasons; the sun knows its setting.'' Both verses highlight God''s intentional design in establishing the celestial bodies to govern time and provide order in creation. This underscores the theme of divine sovereignty over the natural world.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 104:19", "description": "Shows God''s design in celestial bodies and their roles."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and to divide the light from the darkness', 45, 86, 'theology', 'Symbolism of Light and Darkness', 'Many scholars believe that the division of light from darkness is a foundational theological theme representing good and evil, truth and falsehood. This dichotomy is prevalent throughout Scripture, especially in the New Testament, where Jesus is referred to as the light of the world (John 8:12), emphasizing the ongoing battle between spiritual light and darkness.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "John 8:12", "description": "Jesus as the light contrasts with darkness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'God saw that it was good.', 92, 117, 'question', 'Understanding Divine Approval', 'What does it mean for God to declare creation ''good''? This statement invites reflection on the nature of God''s creation and His standards of goodness. How do we discern what is ''good'' in our lives, and how does this understanding affect our actions and choices today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fourth day.', 0, 52, 'connection', 'Creation Timeframe', 'This verse''s structure, emphasizing ''evening'' and ''morning'', parallels the account in Exodus 20:11, highlighting God''s creative authority over time. The rhythm of evening and morning also mirrors the Jewish understanding of a day beginning at sunset, illustrating God''s design in creation. Understanding this can deepen appreciation for the order and intentionality in God''s creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 20:11", "description": "Connects creation to the Sabbath and God''s rest."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fourth day.', 0, 52, 'theology', 'God''s Sovereignty in Time', 'This passage suggests God''s sovereign control over time and creation. The repeated structure of ''evening and morning'' signifies a divine order to the cosmos, reflecting the belief that God is the creator who orchestrates the universe''s timeline. Many scholars see this as foundational to understanding God''s relationship with creation, emphasizing His authority and purpose.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis Commentary by John Calvin", "description": "Explores the theological implications of God''s sovereignty in creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'the fourth day.', 37, 52, 'question', 'Significance of Order', 'What does the designation of ''fourth day'' reveal about God''s intentionality in creation? How might understanding this order influence our view of divine purpose in the world today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fourth day.', 0, 52, 'greek', 'Day Concept', 'יום (yom, H3117) - day, time period. This Hebrew term emphasizes not just a 24-hour cycle but also a designated time of activity and rest, as established by God during creation. The significance of ''day'' in this context points to a divine rhythm inherent in creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3117", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word for ''day''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Let the waters bring forth abundantly the moving creature that hath life, and fowl that may fly above the earth in the open firmament of heaven.', 14, 158, 'connection', 'Creation of Life', 'This verse parallels Genesis 1:24, where God creates living creatures on the earth. Both emphasize God''s sovereignty in creation and His command for life to multiply. The repetition of creation themes underlines the intentionality behind God''s creative work, suggesting a harmonious order in creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:24", "description": "God''s creation of land animals and the command for them to multiply."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Let the waters bring forth abundantly the moving creature that hath life, and fowl that may fly above the earth in the open firmament of heaven.', 14, 158, 'theology', 'God''s Creative Authority', 'This passage illustrates the theological concept of God''s creative authority. Many scholars believe that the command for the waters to bring forth life signifies God''s power to create and sustain life, reflecting His role as the Creator. This foundational truth supports the idea that all creation is under His sovereign will.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Let the waters bring forth abundantly the moving creature that hath life, and fowl that may fly above the earth in the open firmament of heaven.', 14, 158, 'question', 'Reflection on Creation''s Abundance', 'What does it mean for God to command abundance in creation? How does this abundance reflect on His nature and the way we view our stewardship of the earth? Consider how the directive for creatures to multiply can influence our understanding of life and ecological balance.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'And God created great whales', 0, 28, 'connection', 'Creation of Living Beings', 'This phrase reflects God''s sovereignty in creation, which is echoed in Psalm 104:25-26, where the sea is described as teeming with creatures, including the Leviathan. This connection emphasizes the grandeur and variety of God''s creative work and His authority over all creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 104:25-26", "description": "Describes the majesty of sea creatures and God''s creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'which the waters brought forth abundantly', 69, 110, 'theology', 'Abundance in Creation', 'Many scholars believe that the phrase ''brought forth abundantly'' signifies God''s provision and the flourishing of life within creation. This reflects the theological notion that God''s creation is not only good but also designed to thrive, indicating a divine intention for life to flourish.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'after their kind', 112, 128, 'greek', 'Meaning of ''Kind''', 'מִינָה (minah, H4327) - kind, species. This term indicates that God created distinct categories of living beings, emphasizing the diversity within creation while maintaining order. It suggests a divine plan in the ecological balance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H4327", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew word."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'and God saw that it was good.', 168, 197, 'question', 'Understanding ''Good''', 'What does it mean for God to declare creation as ''good''? How does this assessment shape our understanding of the world we live in and our responsibility towards it? Reflecting on the goodness of creation can lead to deeper insights about stewardship and gratitude.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply, and fill the waters in the seas, and let fowl multiply in the earth.', 30, 125, 'connection', 'Creation Mandate', 'This command to ''be fruitful and multiply'' resonates with the broader biblical theme of procreation and stewardship. See also Genesis 9:1, where God reiterates this blessing after the flood, emphasizing the continuation of life and the human role in it. These verses collectively underscore humanity''s responsibility to cultivate and steward creation, reflecting God''s creative intent.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 9:1", "description": "God reaffirms the blessing of multiplication after the flood."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply, and fill the waters in the seas, and let fowl multiply in the earth.', 30, 125, 'theology', 'Divine Blessing', 'This verse reflects the theological concept of divine blessing, where God empowers creation to thrive and reproduce. Many scholars believe that this blessing is not merely a command but also an enabling gift from God, underscoring His desire for creation to flourish. The abundance of life is a testament to God''s goodness and intention for a vibrant creation.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 1:22", "description": "Commentaries explore the implications of God''s blessings in creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply, and fill the waters in the seas, and let fowl multiply in the earth.', 30, 125, 'question', 'Understanding Multiplication', 'What does it mean for us today to ''be fruitful and multiply'' in our lives? How can we apply this command in a modern context, not just in terms of physical reproduction but also in spiritual growth and influencing our communities positively?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fifth day.', 0, 51, 'connection', 'Creation Framework', 'This phrase parallels the creation accounts found in Exodus 20:11, where God rests on the seventh day after creation. The structure of evening and morning captures the rhythm of creation, emphasizing that each day is a distinct period of divine activity. This connection highlights the intentionality of God''s creative process and the establishment of time as a divine framework for humanity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 20:11", "description": "God''s rest after creation, illustrating the completion of His work."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fifth day.', 0, 51, 'theology', 'Divine Order in Creation', 'This passage suggests a theological understanding of time as created and ordered by God. Many scholars believe that the phrase indicates a divinely instituted rhythm of work and rest, which serves as a model for human life. The separation of evening and morning can be seen as a reflection of God''s sovereignty in establishing boundaries and order within creation.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And the evening and the morning were the fifth day.', 0, 51, 'question', 'Understanding Time''s Purpose', 'What significance does the division of evening and morning hold for our understanding of time and God''s creation? How might recognizing this structured rhythm influence our daily lives and our approach to work and rest?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Let the earth bring forth the living creature after his kind', 14, 74, 'connection', 'Creation and Order', 'This phrase resonates with Genesis 1:11, where God commands the earth to bring forth vegetation ''after its kind.'' This connection emphasizes God''s orderly creation process, where each type of living being is designed to reproduce according to its own kind, highlighting the importance of divine intention in the natural order.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 1:11", "description": "God''s command for vegetation, illustrating orderly creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'cattle, and creeping thing, and beast of the earth after his kind', 76, 141, 'theology', 'Diversity in Creation', 'Many scholars believe this phrase underscores the theological concept of biodiversity as part of God''s creative design. Each category of creatures is created with a specific purpose and function, reflecting God''s wisdom and creativity. This diversity serves God''s plan for the earth and highlights the interconnectedness of all living things.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Let the earth bring forth the living creature after his kind', 14, 74, 'question', 'Nature of Creation', 'What does it reveal about God''s character that He commands the earth to bring forth life in such a structured manner? How might this understanding shape our view of stewardship and responsibility toward creation?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'and it was so', 143, 156, 'greek', 'Divine Command', 'ἐγένετο (egeneto, G1096) - to become, to come into existence. This term emphasizes the immediate fulfillment of God''s command, reflecting His sovereignty and the authority of His word in the creation process.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1096", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term used here."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'And God made the beast of the earth after his kind,', 0, 51, 'connection', 'Creation of Beasts', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 104:25-26, where the psalmist reflects on the vast array of creatures God has made. Both passages highlight God''s creative authority and the diversity within creation, emphasizing that each creature serves a purpose in the ecosystem He designed.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 104:25", "description": "Highlights God''s creation and the vastness of the animal kingdom."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'and every thing that creepeth upon the earth after his kind:', 81, 141, 'theology', 'God''s Order in Creation', 'Many scholars believe this phrase reflects the theological principle of order in God''s creation. Each creature is made ''after his kind,'' suggesting that God created with intentionality and purpose, which is foundational to understanding the created order and the harmony of life.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 1:25", "description": "Discusses the order and purpose in God''s creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'and God saw that it was good.', 142, 171, 'question', 'Understanding ''Good''', 'What does it mean for God to declare His creation as ''good''? In what ways does this affirmation challenge us to view our relationship with creation and our responsibility towards it? How does recognizing the goodness of creation impact our stewardship today?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Let us make man in our image, after our likeness:', 14, 63, 'connection', 'Creation in God''s Image', 'This phrase echoes Genesis 5:1, where it states, ''In the day that God created man, in the likeness of God made he him.'' The connection emphasizes the sacredness of humanity, as being made in God''s image signifies a unique relationship and responsibility. It invites readers to reflect on the inherent value of all human life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 5:1", "description": "Further elaborates on humanity''s creation in God''s likeness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'let them have dominion over the fish of the sea, and over the fowl of the air, and over the cattle, and over all the earth, and over every creeping thing that creepeth upon the earth.', 68, 251, 'theology', 'Human Authority and Stewardship', 'This passage suggests that humanity has a divinely appointed authority over creation, indicating a role of stewardship rather than exploitation. Many scholars believe this reflects the responsibility to care for the earth, highlighting themes of ecological balance and respect for all living beings as part of God''s creation.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'in our image, after our likeness:', 30, 63, 'greek', 'Theological Significance of ''Image''', 'צֶלֶם (tselem, H6754) - image, likeness. This Hebrew word denotes a representation or reflection of something. In this context, it underscores that humans reflect God''s nature, setting them apart from other creatures and endowing them with dignity and purpose.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6754", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'Let us make man in our image, after our likeness:', 14, 63, 'question', 'Reflection on Divine Image', 'What does it mean to be created in the image of God, and how should this understanding influence our relationships with others and the environment? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation of human dignity and our role as caretakers of creation.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'in his own image,', 19, 36, 'theology', 'Imago Dei Concept', 'The phrase ''in his own image'' introduces the theological concept of Imago Dei, which asserts that humans reflect God''s character and nature. This has profound implications for human dignity, ethics, and relationships. Many scholars believe that this likeness includes moral, spiritual, and relational attributes, setting humanity apart from the rest of creation, as articulated in various theological works.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis 1:26-27", "description": "Explores the significance of humanity''s creation in God''s image."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'male and female created he them.', 73, 105, 'connection', 'Gender in Creation', 'This declaration of male and female being created together emphasizes the equality and complementarity of genders. It connects to Matthew 19:4, where Jesus references Genesis to underscore the divine intention for marriage and human relationships. Understanding this connection helps clarify God''s design for gender roles and relationships in both the family and the church.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 19:4", "description": "Jesus refers to the creation of male and female to discuss marriage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'So God created man', 0, 18, 'question', 'Understanding Creation', 'What does it mean for God to have actively created humanity? How does recognizing God as the Creator influence our understanding of purpose and identity? Reflecting on this can deepen our appreciation for God''s intentionality in creation.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 27, 27, 'kjv', 'in the image of God created he him;', 37, 72, 'greek', 'Greek Term for Image', 'צֶלֶם (tselem, H6754) - image, likeness. This Hebrew word conveys the notion of representation or reflection, underscoring that humanity is a representation of God''s attributes on earth. Understanding this term enriches our comprehension of what it means to be made in God''s image.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H6754", "description": "Strong''s definition and usage of ''image'' in the Old Testament."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'Be fruitful, and multiply, and replenish the earth, and subdue it', 46, 111, 'connection', 'Creation Mandate', 'This command to ''be fruitful and multiply'' connects with Genesis 9:1, where God reiterates this blessing after the flood, emphasizing the continuity of God''s plan for humanity to fill and steward the earth. It reflects God''s desire for humanity to thrive and exercise responsible dominion over creation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 9:1", "description": "Reinforces God''s ongoing command for multiplication and stewardship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'have dominion over the fish of the sea, and over the fowl of the air', 117, 185, 'theology', 'Human Stewardship', 'This verse encapsulates the theological concept of stewardship, where humanity is appointed as caretakers of God''s creation. Many scholars believe this indicates a responsibility to manage and protect the environment, reflecting God''s character and intention for harmony between humanity and nature.', 'person.2.fill', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Genesis Commentary by John Walton", "description": "Discusses the implications of human dominion and stewardship."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'God blessed them', 4, 20, 'greek', 'Divine Favor', 'בָּרַךְ (barak, H1288) - to bless, to confer prosperity. This term signifies not only a spoken blessing but the impartation of divine favor and empowerment for the tasks assigned to humanity, illustrating God''s intimate involvement in creation.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1288", "description": "Strong''s Hebrew number for ''to bless''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 28, 28, 'kjv', 'replenish the earth', 77, 96, 'question', 'Understanding Replenishment', 'What does it mean for humanity to ''replenish the earth'' in a way that honors God''s creation? How can we actively participate in restoration and sustainability in our current context?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 1, 29, 29, 'kjv', 'every herb bearing seed, which is upon the face of all the earth, and every tree, in the which is the fruit of a tree yielding seed;', 39, 171, 'connection', 'Creation and Provision', 'This phrase connects to Matthew 6:26, where Jesus teaches that God provides for all creatures. Both passages reflect God''s provision in creation, emphasizing His care for life. This highlights the continuity of God''s creation and sustenance across both the Old and New Testaments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:26", "description": "Jesus illustrates God''s provision for His creation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');